Financial services group Sanlam has published its annual report, revealing how much the companies top executives were paid in 2018. In March the insurer announced its operational results for the 12 months ended December 2018, which also included the acquisition of the remaining 53% stake in Saham Finances, the largest transaction in Sanlam’s 100-year history. Results for 2018 included 14% growth in the value of new life insurance business (VNB) on a consistent economic basis and more than R2 billion in positive experience variances. Key features of the 2018 annual results included: Net result from financial services increased by 4% compared to the same period in 2017;
Net operating profit of R2.04 billion, up 14%;
Diluted headline earnings per share f 441.1 cents, down 8%;
Net value of new covered business up 8% to R2 billion (up 14% on a consistent economic basis);
Net fund inflows of R42 billion compared to R37 billion in 2017;
Adjusted Return on Group Equity Value per share of 19.4% exceeded the target of 13%; and
Dividend per share of 312 cents, up 8%. <img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-308672" src="https://businesstech.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/Sanlam.png" alt="" width="687" height="445" srcset="https://businesstech.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/Sanlam.png 687w, https://businesstech.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/Sanlam-300x194.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 709px) 85vw, (max-width: 909px) 67vw, (max-width: 984px) 61vw, (max-width: 1362px) 45vw, 600px" /> Sanlam CEO Ian Kirk took home R31.05 million for the year, including a basic salary of R8.91 million, an annual bonus of R11 million, and long-term incentives valued at R10.93 million. This works out to R85,000 a day. Kirk was the highest paid executive on the team, followed by chief actuary and group risk officer, Anton Gildenhuys, who earned R19.09 million for the year. In total, Sanlam’s executive committee was paid a combined R139.7 million for the year, averaging R17.5 million per person. <img class="aligncenter wp-image-308662" src="https://businesstech.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/Sanlam-salaries.png" alt="" width="960" height="282" srcset="https://businesstech.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/Sanlam-salaries.png 2788w, https://businesstech.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/Sanlam-salaries-300x88.png 300w, https://businesstech.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/Sanlam-salaries-768x225.png 768w, https://businesstech.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/Sanlam-salaries-1024x300.png 1024w, https://businesstech.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/Sanlam-salaries-1200x352.png 1200w" sizes="(max-width: 709px) 85vw, (max-width: 909px) 67vw, (max-width: 1362px) 62vw, 840px" /> Kirk’s salary is 76 times larger than the average salary paid to employees in the period (R410,039 including short-term benefits), and around 128 times larger than the average salary in South Africa Stats SA’s latest Quarterly Employment Survey, showed that the average employee in South Africa earned R20,190 a month, or R242,280 a a year. The table below outlines what Sanlam’s executives earned, and how that translates to an average per day (365 days). Read: MTN’s boss earns R117,600 a day